author: Primrose Riordan
title: EU trade deal a 'missing piece', Andrew Robb says
text:
Andrew Robb: "Having concluded landmark trade deals with the major economies of North Asia in Korea, Japan and China, along with negotiations for the 12-country Trans Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP); the EU presented something of a missing piece." Andrew Meares Share on twitter Share on Google Plus by Primrose Riordan Trade Minister Andrew Robb has said the European trade deal was a "missing piece" in Australia's approach to free trade, after a European Commission announcement moved Australia's bid for the agreement a step closer.
The European Commission said it would seek authorisation from its 28 members to open separate negotiations with "close partners" Australia and New Zealand in its new trade and investment strategy announced on Wednesday.
Mr Robb said the announcement identified Australia as a priority negotiating partner for a free trade agreement.
"Having concluded landmark trade deals with the major economies of North Asia in Korea, Japan and China, along with negotiations for the 12-country Trans Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP); the EU presented something of a missing piece," Mr Robb said.
In the next step, the commission needs to seek authorisation from the EU's 28 member countries to get the deal completed.
The trade deal with Europe was signalled at last November's G20 meeting in Brisbane.
